3️⃣ SOLID Principles (Very Important) — 25 min

These are must-know principles for clean, maintainable, scalable code. Every Java/Spring interview will ask this.

S — Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)

One class = One responsibility

❌ Bad:

AccountService handles DB + Validation + Email + Logging

✅ Good:

AccountService → business logic

AccountRepository → DB

NotificationService → Email/SMS

Benefit: Easy testing, easy maintenance

O — Open/Closed Principle (OCP)

Open for extension, Closed for modification

You should add new behavior without changing old code.

Example:

interface InterestCalculator {
    double calculate(double balance);
}


Add new types:

class SavingsInterest implements InterestCalculator {}
class CurrentInterest implements InterestCalculator {}


No need to modify old code 👍

L — Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)

Child class should replace parent class without breaking behavior

Example:
If SavingsAccount extends Account, it should behave like Account — not break logic.

Bad example:
If withdrawal not allowed in child → violates LSP ❌

I — Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)

Don’t force classes to implement unused methods

❌ Bad:

interface BankOperations {
    void deposit();
    void withdraw();
    void loan();
}


If some class doesn't need loan → problem ❌

✅ Good:

interface Deposit { void deposit(); }
interface Withdraw { void withdraw(); }
interface Loan { void loan(); }

D — Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)

Depend on abstraction, not concrete class

❌ Bad:

class AccountService {
    private MySQLAccountRepository repo = new MySQLAccountRepository();
}


✅ Good:

class AccountService {
    private AccountRepository repo;
}


Spring does this using @Autowired / Constructor Injection

