Domain-Driven Design (DDD) Basics — 20 min
1️⃣ What is DDD?

Domain-Driven Design = Designing software based on real business rules.

Focus is business logic first, not database or framework.

Example (Banking):

Account must never go negative ❌

Transfer must be atomic

Only ACTIVE account can transact

Debit + Credit must be consistent

These rules = Domain Logic

2️⃣ Core Concepts of DDD
1. Domain

The business problem area you are solving.

For you:

Banking System Domain


Subdomains:

Account

Transaction

User

Payment

Notification

2. Entity

Object with unique identity + lifecycle

Example:

AccountEntity
TransactionEntity
UserEntity


Even if balance changes → still same Account (same ID)

3. Value Object

Object without identity (compared by value)

Examples in Banking:

Money

Address

Email

PhoneNumber

public class Money {
    private BigDecimal amount;
    private String currency;
}


No ID → only value matters.

4. Aggregate

Group of related objects treated as single unit

Example:

Account Aggregate
 ├── Account (Root)
 ├── Transactions


Only Aggregate Root can be accessed directly.

5. Aggregate Root

Main controller of the aggregate.

Example:

Account


All operations must go through Account:

debit()

credit()

block()

Never directly modify Transaction list from outside ❌

6. Repository

Handles database access for Aggregates

AccountRepository
TransactionRepository


DDD Rule:

Repository works only with Aggregate Roots

7. Domain Service

When logic doesn’t belong to single entity

Example:

Money Transfer between two accounts

Fraud detection

Interest calculation

TransferService

8. Application Service

Orchestrates use cases

Example:

Create Account

Transfer Money

Get Balance

Calls:

Domain entities

