5️⃣ DTO vs Entity — 10 min
1️⃣ What is an Entity?

Entity = Database table mapped object (JPA/Hibernate).

Has @Entity

Represents DB structure

Contains business data

Managed by Hibernate

Example:

@Entity
@Table(name = "accounts")
public class AccountEntity {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long accountId;

    private String name;
    private BigDecimal balance;
    private String status;
}


Entity = DB Model

2️⃣ What is DTO?

DTO = Data Transfer Object (used for API communication).

Used between Controller ⇄ Client

Not mapped to DB

Only contains required fields

No business logic

Example:

public class AccountDTO {

    private Long accountId;
    private String name;
    private BigDecimal balance;
}


DTO = API Model

3️⃣ Why NOT expose Entity directly? ❌
Problem 1 — Security Risk

Entity may contain:

password

internal fields

audit data

DTO hides sensitive data.

Problem 2 — Tight Coupling

If DB changes → API breaks ❌
DTO protects API contract.

Problem 3 — Lazy Loading Issues

Entities may have relationships:

@OneToMany(fetch = LAZY)
List<Transaction> transactions;


Returning entity → LazyInitializationException

DTO avoids this.

Problem 4 — Over-fetching Data

Entity may contain many fields → API slow ❌
DTO sends only required data.

4️⃣ DTO vs Entity Comparison
Feature	Entity	DTO
DB Mapping	Yes	No
Used in Repository	Yes	No
Used in Controller	❌ Avoid	Yes
Business Logic	Sometimes	No
Serializable for API	Not recommended	Yes
Security Safe	No	Yes
5️⃣ Flow in Spring Boot
Controller ⇄ DTO ⇄ Service ⇄ Entity ⇄ Repository ⇄ DB

6️⃣ Mapping Example
Convert Entity → DTO
public AccountDTO toDTO(AccountEntity entity) {
    AccountDTO dto = new AccountDTO();
    dto.setAccountId(entity.getAccountId());
    dto.setName(entity.getName());
    dto.setBalance(entity.getBalance());
    return dto;
}

Convert DTO → Entity
public AccountEntity toEntity(AccountDTO dto) {
    AccountEntity entity = new AccountEntity();
    entity.setName(dto.getName());
    entity.setBalance(dto.getBalance());
    return entity;
}

7️⃣ Best Practice (Industry)

Use Mapper Class or MapStruct

Example:

@Mapper(componentModel = "spring")
public interface AccountMapper {
    AccountDTO toDTO(AccountEntity entity);
    AccountEntity toEntity(AccountDTO dto);
}

